<hl>
<seg id=1> Two Soldiers of South Korea Who Were Taken Prisoner in Korean War Fled from North Korea after 45 Years Imprisonment </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Reuters, Seoul) National Security Planning Burearu of South Korea said the day before that two South Korean soldiers who had been put on the death list of Korean War recently ran away from North Korea after being imprisoned for at least 45 years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> National Security Planning Bureau stated that Jin Fuji, 67, and Piao Dongyi, 71, have lately returned to South Korea via a third country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The statement said that the two men were captured by Chinese soldiers in the northeast area near the border of South Korea and North Korea during the Korean War. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The statement said that the two men were forced to work as slave workers in a North Korea's coal mine before running away. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> South Korean Defence Ministry, after the Korean War happening from 1950 to 1953, put the name of tens of thousands of missing soldiers on the death list, Jin Fuji and Piao Dongyi being two of them. </seg>
<seg id=7> What South Korea and North Korea finally signed was a ceasefire agreement other than a formal peace treaty. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> South Korea and North Korea technically are still in the state of war. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It is unexpected that the two men should have become marriage relatives during imprisonment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> The statement said that Jin Fuji's second-born son Jin Ningqiu and Piao Dongyi's fourth-born daughter Piao Zhengxin got married in April 1991. </seg>
<seg id=11> The statement didn't have any further explanation. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> An official from National Security Planning Bureau said that Jin Fuji and Piao Dongyi currently are detainded for questioning. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Dedence Ministry once expressed that about twenty thousand soldiers were missing during the Korean War. Defence Ministry believes that there are some more survivors. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> This April an escaped POW said that he knew now 50 or 60 more South Korean soldiers were imprisoned in North Korea. </seg>
</p>
